She turned to a blank page and noted the date. Below, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Are you reading old memories?" Ivory asked as she looked at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you go out for Christmas? It's only a few days away."
Kari tapped twice on the lantern. No. Ivory had been right. The Ice King never let Kari out, because she was an "error" in his eyes. She was born mute, and she was the only girl in a family otherwise entirely composed of boys.
Ivory was also that way, in her own way. When she had mentioned her non-binary identity, it felt like the world had shifted. They had given her tasks that condemned her to solitude as punishment for her difference.
Iel also had to remain in service to the princess, but that wasn't too big of a deal since it made her a friend.
"It's close to your birthday, I think," Ivory asked, remembering that the princess's birthday was coming up in a few days. Kari nodded, a sad glimmer in her pale blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate it?" As iel asked, iel remembered what she had answered last time.
No, Kari struck back with a tap. Ivory knew it was a sensitive topic for her. It was the day she was confined to her room and her mother was banished. Ivory was still a baby when that happened, but iel remembered the indignation of the servants and the residents. iel had heard that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but she also had this strange ability to predict the future.
"Well... what do you feel like doing?" iel asked. Kari looked up with enthusiasm. She handed a piece of paper to Ivory. But when iel glanced at it...
15 cm x 15 cm Painting
White, several shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"Do you want me to find these things for you?" Ivory asked, turning towards the silent princess who was tapping frenetically, shaking her pigtails back and forth. "Yes?" Iel giggled slightly, seeing the usually reserved princess passionate about something. This was the first time she had asked for something not related to books and not found in her room.
"Okay. See you later?" Ivory proposed as she stood up and made her way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded and immersed herself in her memories again, wrapping herself tightly in her thick comforter.
Iel left the room with relief. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things outside her usual scope, like painting supplies.
Iel turned back down the corridors, trying not to listen to the whispers of the maids.
"I heard she's possessed by Queen Eirwen, which is why she always goes into that room."
"I heard she eats children in that room."
"She looks like a man, doesn't she?"
Iel covered her ears, because ignoring it didn't work. Iel headed toward the royal painter's room, which was located in the east wing, second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was as intricately carved as Kari's. It featured a white dragon, one of the six primordial dragons, according to legend, who had created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to display such artwork on his door. He loved history.
Iel opened the door, expecting to find a typical scene. Dried paint spots everywhere, scattered pencils and papers in the room, easels covering every inch of the wall. Surprisingly, there was nothing like that. The room was clean, with a red velvet backdrop and a stool just in front of it. On the stool, Prince Aquilo was posing for his portrait.
"Oh hello, Ivory! Are you here to watch your future king pose for a portrait?" Aquilo asked Ivory with a wink.
"Pardon, petit prince," répondit iel en l'ignorant partiellement, pour chercher les objets que sa silencieuse amie souhaitait. "Je suis là juste pour récupérer des fournitures."
"Ah, la fillette va repartir très vite ?" demanda Aquilo, "Mais je voulais te voir !"
"Eh bien, pas moi." Ivory avait trouvé les fournitures d'art de sa liste et les avait placées dans une caisse qu'iel avait dénichée. "Et je ne suis pas une fille."
Le prince n'y avait pas pensé toutefois. "Oh ma chérie, tu sais bien que c'est juste une phase ! Ça te passera quand tu auras grandi !", marmonna-t-il.
"Je dois y aller," dit iel, soudain mal à l'aise, à cause des paroles du prince, qui lui rappelaient tout le mal que les gens disaient au sujet de son identité de genre. Je veux vraiment m'éloigner de lui.
"Aren't you leaving already?" The Prince appeared at the door immediately, ignoring the complaints of the royal painter.
"That's not the behavior of a future king!" he scolded.
"No one will know. Others won't believe you, and the painter won't say anything if he values his life." He turned to the painter for a moment, then leaned towards Ivory. "What do you say to a romantic rendezvous?" Iel shuddered. Indeed, iel had received many threats before, but never from a prince, especially one who was the heir to the throne.
"Do you not know what the word no means?" she said, pushing the prince out of her way.
"Heck no," replied Aquilo with a smile. Of course, a prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what that word means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why want a romantic rendezvous with me instead of someone else? You must have a hundred suitors?"
He interrupted her, still smiling broadly: "500, to be exact." He tossed his hair back, sending it flying in the cold air.
Then, why me instead of another? I am the palace threat." Iel wrapped her arms around her body.
You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo placed his finger under her chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
